hook.real_world_problem:
You've built `OrderService.placeOrder()`. It:
1. Validates the order
2. Saves to the database (via `OrderRepository`)
3. Sends a confirmation email (via `EmailService`)
4. Returns the saved order with a generated ID

How do you test this? You can't set up a real database and email server for every test run. They're slow, fragile, and produce real side effects.

```java
// WITHOUT mocking — tests need real infrastructure:
class OrderServiceTest {
    OrderService service = new OrderService(
        new RealOrderRepository("jdbc:postgresql://..."),  // real DB!
        new RealEmailService("smtp.gmail.com")             // real email!
    );
    // If DB is down → tests fail. If email quota exceeded → tests fail.
    // Each test inserts real data that needs cleanup.
}
```

**WITH Mockito:**
```java
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)
class OrderServiceTest {
    @Mock OrderRepository repo;    // fake — no real DB
    @Mock EmailService emailSvc;   // fake — no real emails
    @InjectMocks OrderService service;  // service gets the fakes

    @Test
    void placeOrder_validOrder_savesAndSendsEmail() {
        Order order = new Order("Mouse", 2, 799);
        Order saved = order.withId("ORD-001");

        when(repo.save(order)).thenReturn(saved);  // fake save returns saved order

        Order result = service.placeOrder(order);

        assertEquals("ORD-001", result.getId());
        verify(repo).save(order);          // verify save was called
        verify(emailSvc).sendConfirmation(saved);  // verify email was sent
    }
}
```

Zero real infrastructure. Test runs in milliseconds. Side effects controlled.

concept_explanation.mockito_setup:
**Mockito setup:**

```xml
<!-- pom.xml -->
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.mockito</groupId>
    <artifactId>mockito-junit-jupiter</artifactId>
    <version>5.5.0</version>
    <scope>test</scope>
</dependency>
```

**Two ways to create mocks:**
```java
// Option 1: Annotation-based (preferred):
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)  // class annotation
class OrderServiceTest {
    @Mock OrderRepository repo;    // creates a mock
    @InjectMocks OrderService service; // creates service and injects @Mock fields
}

// Option 2: Programmatic (for one-off mocks):
OrderRepository repo = Mockito.mock(OrderRepository.class);
OrderService service = new OrderService(repo);
```

**What `@InjectMocks` does:**
Creates an instance of OrderService and automatically injects all `@Mock` fields into it (via constructor, setters, or field injection — tries each in order).

concept_explanation.stubbing:
**Stubbing — controlling what mocks return:**

```java
import static org.mockito.Mockito.*;

// when(methodCall).thenReturn(value):
when(repo.findById("U01")).thenReturn(Optional.of(user));
when(repo.findById("U99")).thenReturn(Optional.empty());

// Return different values on successive calls:
when(repo.count()).thenReturn(5L, 6L, 7L);
// First call → 5, second call → 6, third+ → 7

// Return value based on argument:
when(repo.findById(anyString())).thenReturn(Optional.empty());  // default
when(repo.findById("U01")).thenReturn(Optional.of(aisha));      // specific override

// Stub void methods:
doNothing().when(emailService).send(any());  // do nothing when called

// thenAnswer for dynamic responses:
when(repo.save(any())).thenAnswer(invocation -> {
    Order o = invocation.getArgument(0);
    return o.withId("ORD-" + o.product().toUpperCase());
});
```

