concept_explanation.verify:
**verify() — check that methods were called:**

```java
// Basic verify — method was called exactly once:
verify(repo).save(order);
verify(emailSvc).sendConfirmation(savedOrder);

// Verify with specific arguments:
verify(repo).save(order);                        // exactly this order
verify(repo).findById("U01");                    // exactly this ID

// Verify call count:
verify(repo, times(2)).save(any());              // called exactly 2 times
verify(repo, times(0)).delete(any());            // never called
verify(repo, never()).delete(any());             // same as times(0)
verify(repo, atLeast(1)).findById(anyString());  // at least once
verify(repo, atMost(3)).findById(anyString());   // at most 3 times

// Verify no more interactions:
verifyNoMoreInteractions(repo);  // no other methods called on repo
verifyNoInteractions(emailSvc);  // nothing was called on emailSvc

// Verify order of calls:
InOrder inOrder = inOrder(repo, emailSvc);
inOrder.verify(repo).save(order);             // save called first
inOrder.verify(emailSvc).sendConfirmation(savedOrder);  // then email
```

concept_explanation.argument_matchers:
**Argument matchers — flexible verification:**

```java
import static org.mockito.ArgumentMatchers.*;

// any() — matches any object of any type:
when(repo.save(any())).thenReturn(savedOrder);
verify(repo).save(any(Order.class));

// anyString(), anyInt(), anyLong(), anyDouble(), anyBoolean():
when(repo.findById(anyString())).thenReturn(Optional.empty());

// eq() — exact match (use when mixing matchers):
when(repo.findByNameAndDept(eq("Aisha"), anyString())).thenReturn(user);
// RULE: if you use ANY matcher, ALL args must be matchers:
// WRONG: when(repo.find("Aisha", anyString()))  — mix of literal and matcher
// RIGHT: when(repo.find(eq("Aisha"), anyString()))

// contains(), startsWith(), endsWith() for strings:
when(emailSvc.sendTo(contains("@flipkart"))).thenReturn(true);

// isNull(), isNotNull():
when(repo.save(isNotNull())).thenReturn(savedOrder);
```

concept_explanation.argument_captor:
**ArgumentCaptor — capture what was passed:**

```java
@Captor ArgumentCaptor<Order> orderCaptor;
// OR programmatic:
ArgumentCaptor<Order> orderCaptor = ArgumentCaptor.forClass(Order.class);

@Test
void placeOrder_setsCorrectStatus() {
    service.placeOrder(new Order("Mouse", 2, 799));

    // Capture what was passed to repo.save():
    verify(repo).save(orderCaptor.capture());
    Order capturedOrder = orderCaptor.getValue();

    // Now assert on the captured value:
    assertEquals(OrderStatus.PENDING, capturedOrder.getStatus());
    assertEquals(2,   capturedOrder.getQty());
    assertEquals(799, capturedOrder.getPrice());
    assertNotNull(capturedOrder.getTimestamp());
}
```

ArgumentCaptor is essential when you need to verify not just THAT a method was called, but exactly WHAT was passed to it.

concept_explanation.spy:
**Spy — partially mock a real object:**

```java
// Mock: entirely fake — no real methods called
// Spy: real object with specific methods overridden

List<String> realList = new ArrayList<>();
List<String> spyList  = Mockito.spy(realList);

// Real methods work:
spyList.add("hello");
System.out.println(spyList.size());  // 1 (real call)

// Stub specific methods:
doReturn(10).when(spyList).size();   // fake size()
System.out.println(spyList.size());  // 10 (stubbed)

// Use spy for classes where most behaviour is real but one method needs stubbing:
// Common use: spy on a service to test one method while calling real implementations of others

// NOTE: Use doReturn().when(spy) NOT when(spy).thenReturn() for spy methods
// (when() calls the real method first, which may have side effects)
```

